<solution><div><h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>To find the center, foci, and determine whether specific points lie on the ellipse, we can follow these steps:</p>
<p>Given information:</p>
<p>- Major axis endpoints: <m> A(0, {5}) </m> and <m> B(0, -{5}) </m> </p>
<p>- Minor axis endpoints: <m> C({4}, 0) </m> and <m> D({-4}, 0) </m></p>

<p><alert>Step 1: Find the Center of the Ellipse</alert></p>

<p>The center of an ellipse is the midpoint of the endpoints of the major axis. We can find it using the formula for the midpoint of two points <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2)</m>:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>\text{Center} = \displaystyle \left(\frac{x_1 + x_2}{2}, \frac{y_1 + y_2}{2}\right)</m></p>

<p>In this case, the endpoints of the major axis are <m>\displaystyle (0, {5}) </m> and <m>\displaystyle (0, -{5}) </m>, so the center is:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>\text{Center} = \displaystyle \left(\frac{0 + 0}{2}, \frac{{5} + (-{5})}{2}\right) = (0, 0)</m></p>

<p><alert>Step 2: Find the Coordinates of the Foci</alert></p>

<p>The distance from the center to each focus is given by the equation:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>c =\displaystyle \sqrt{a^2 - b^2}</m></p>

<p>where <m>a</m> is the length of the semi-major axis and <m>b</m> is the length of the semi-minor axis.</p>

<p>Given the endpoints of the minor axis, we can calculate the length of the semi-minor axis <m>b</m>:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>b =\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} \cdot \text{distance}(C, D) =\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} \cdot \sqrt{({4} - (-{4}))^2 + (0 - 0)^2} = {4}</m></p>

<p>Given the endpoints of the major axis, we can calculate the length of the semi-major axis <m>a</m>:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>a =\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} \cdot \text{distance}(A, B) = \displaystyle \frac{1}{2} \cdot \sqrt{(0 - 0)^2 + ({5} - (-{5}))^2} = {5}</m></p>

<p>Now we can calculate the distance from the center to each focus:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>c = \displaystyle \sqrt{a^2 - b^2} = \sqrt{{5}^2 - {4}^2}= \displaystyle {3}</m></p>

<p>The foci will be located along the major axis, which is the <m>y</m>-axis. So, the coordinates of the foci are:</p>

<p>Foci: <m>\displaystyle (0,  {3} ) </m> and <m>\displaystyle (0,  -{3}) </m> </p>

<p><alert>Step 3: Determine if Specific Points are on the Ellipse</alert></p>

<p>The equation of an ellipse with center <m>(h, k)</m>, semi-major axis <m>a</m>, and semi-minor axis <m>b</m> is given by:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>\displaystyle \frac{(x - h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y - k)^2}{b^2} = 1</m></p>

<p>In this case, the center is <m>(0, 0)</m>, <m>a = \displaystyle {5}</m>, and <m>b =\displaystyle {4}</m>. We can now check whether each point lies on the ellipse:</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">(i) <m>({-4}, \, {-5})</m>:</p>
<p>Substituting the coordinates into the ellipse equation:</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>\displaystyle \frac{({-4}-0)^2}{{5}^2} + \frac{({-5}-0)^2}{{4}^2} ={\frac{16}{25}} + {\frac{25}{16}}= {\frac{881}{400}}</m></p>
<p>So, this point is not on the ellipse.</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">(ii) <m>\displaystyle ({0}, \, {4})</m>:</p>
<p>Substituting the coordinates into the ellipse equation:</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m> \displaystyle \frac{({0}-0)^2}{{5}^2} + \frac{({4}-0)^2}{{4}^2} ={0} + {1}= {1} </m></p>
<p>So, this point is on  the ellipse.</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">(iii) <m>\displaystyle ({-5}, \, {-3})</m>:</p>
<p>Substituting the coordinates into the ellipse equation:
</p><p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>\displaystyle \frac{({-5}-0)^2}{{5}^2} + \frac{({-3}-0)^2}{{4}^2} ={1} + {\frac{9}{16}} = {\frac{25}{16}}</m></p>
<p>So, this point is not on the ellipse.</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">(iv) <m>\displaystyle ({-5}, \, {0})</m>:</p>
<p>Substituting the coordinates into the ellipse equation:</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px"><m>\displaystyle \frac{({-5}-0)^2}{{5}^2} + \frac{({0}-0)^2}{{4}^2} ={1}+ {0}= {1}</m></p>
<p>So, this point is on  the ellipse.</p></div></solution>
